May 24, 2026: Bosly Keep v4.0 — Trading Engine Redesign
The engine was fundamentally rearchitected to align with Bosly Keep's long-term wealth philosophy. The original design used short-term trading logic (take-profit at +6%, stop-loss at -8%) that directly contradicted the app's core promise of long-term compounding.
Philosophy:
- Bosly Keep is for building wealth over years, not trading over days - A 6% price move is noise, not a reason to sell a good company
- The best action with a winning investment is usually to do nothing - Selling should only happen when something fundamental changes—not when a price wiggles
New Parameters:
- Allocation per trade: 10% of available cash - Max trades per day: 5
- Min funds threshold: £20

 - Max price threshold: £100 GBP
- Fractional shares: Enabled
- Max portfolio weight per holding: 20% (triggers review)
- Ethical score drop threshold: 15 points (triggers sell)
- Review after gain: 25% (triggers "holding well" review, not sell) - Review after holding: 90 days (triggers time-based check-in)
Signal Types:
Buy — An ethical asset not yet owned. Spread across sectors, prioritised by ethical score. Plain-English reason explains the company, its ethical category, its score, and what buying means for cash and ownership.
Sell — Only triggered by an ethical score drop of 15+ points. The company's behaviour has changed meaningfully and it may no longer belong in an ethical portfolio. Reason explains what dropped, by how much, and why it matters.
Review — Two triggers: (1) A single holding exceeds 20% of total portfolio—a concentration risk nudge, not a quality judgement. (2) A holding has been in the portfolio for 90+ days—a routine check-in.
Holding Well — A holding is up 25%+ since purchase. A celebration signal, not an instruction. Reinforces the long-term behaviour: winners should be left to compound. No sell button is shown.
Removed:
- ~~Stop loss (-8%)~~ — Short-term losses are normal. Selling locks them in
- ~~Take profit (+6%)~~ — Cutting winners early destroys compounding
Plain-English Design: Every signal answers three questions in language a first-time investor can understand: What are you suggesting? Why now? What happens if I say yes?
